Part A – Case Study -Phishing

Title: Phishing Attack on a College Student
Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers deceive people into giving up sensitive information like passwords, bank details, or OTPs by pretending to be a trusted source.
A typical scenario involves a college student receiving an email that seems to be from their bank or a popular payment app. The message warns that their account will be blocked unless they verify their details right away. It includes a link that looks legitimate but actually leads to a fake website designed to mimic the original.
The student, without checking if the email is real, clicks the link and enters their login details and OTP. Within minutes, unauthorized transactions occur from their account.
Phishing attacks often target students and others who may not fully understand online security practices. The results can be financial loss, identity theft, and unauthorized access to personal accounts.
This case emphasizes the need to be cautious when clicking links, verifying sources, and never sharing sensitive information online.

Part B – Prevention Checklist -Stay Safe Online
General Safety Tips:
•	Don’t click on suspicious links in emails or messages.
•	Always check the sender’s email address before responding.
•	Use strong and unique passwords for different accounts.
•	Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) whenever possible.
•	Avoid public Wi-Fi for sensitive transactions.
•	Keep your devices and apps up to date.

UPI / Financial Safety:
•	Never share your OTP, PIN, or banking details with anyone.
•	Always verify UPI IDs before making payments.
•	Don’t approve unfamiliar payment requests.
•	Use only official apps for transactions.

Reporting:
•	Report cybercrime at: [https://cybercrime.gov.in](https://cybercrime.gov.in)
•	Call helpline: **1930**

